title: For Sale:  Pair of SAPI Plates, Size Large
postcontent:
SAPI (Small Arms Protective Insert) Plates
For sale is a set of genuine SAPI plates, size Large

Description:
The Small Arms Protective Insert (SAPI) is a ceramic plate fielded by the US military. It was first used in the Interceptor body armor, a ballistic vest. It is now also used in the Improved Outer Tactical Vest as well as the Modular Tactical Vest, in addition to commercially available "plate carriers". The kevlar Interceptor vest itself is designed to stop projectiles up to and including 9x19mm Parabellum submachine gun rounds, in addition to fragmentation. To protect against higher velocity rifle rounds, SAPI or ESAPI plates are needed.

Materials and capabilities
The standard plate for the Interceptor body armor is made of boron carbide or silicon carbide ceramic.  The standard plates are not given an NIJ rating, as they are tested in accordance with specific protocols for the military and not the NIJ's testing. Military testing calls for survivability of three hits from the round marked on the plate - for standard SAPI, of a caliber up to 7.62x51mm NATO M80 ball and of a muzzle velocity up to 2,750 ft/s (840 m/s). This performance is only assured when backed by the soft armor of the OTV (or any soft armor which meets military requirements for protection. The ceramic plate is backed with a shield made of Spectra, a material up to 40% stronger than Kevlar, to trap any fragments of either plate or projectile and prevent them from injuring the wearer.

Item Condition:  Used Excellent- No Cracks or other damage

title: For Sale/Trade:  UNION SWITCH SIGNAL 1911
postcontent:
UPDATE:  I recently was informed by a knowldgeable collecter this pistol has some problems that could effect its value.  The gun has been re-finished or parkerized at some point instead of maintaining its original finish.  This explains the faintness of the markings.  Also the rear sight - which has some damage is installed backward.  I post this new info in good faith because I do not want to mis-represent the gun in any way to any potential buyer. The gun is still very rare with correct parts except for the grips.  It is still collectable or has value for the individual parts.  Due to this new information, I am open to all offers above my investment.

Very rare 45 cal. model 1911 manufactured by Union Switch & Signal in 1943.  This gun is complete with all correctly parts except the wooden grips.  Correct plastic grips are easily found.  The markings and stamps are correct to include the slide, frame and barrel.  The gun does function properly but should be considered a collectable - not a shooter, because of its rarity and value.  The USS models were the only manufacturer which passed all US. Army acceptance testing.  Only the Singer models had fewer produced.

The USS markings on the left side of the slide are faint as is the RCD inspection stamp and proof marks but all are readible.  The sn, model marks on the right frame are very clear.  The barrel is correct but does show some bore wear.  The frame/slide fit is loose as was most of the issued service models.  The rear sight has some drop damage which slightly flattened the right ear. I can provide more pictures to those interested.  This gun will never loose its value and will only become more collectable in the future.
